<LEADPARA>  Q  Along I-505, a cutoff between I-80 and I-5 35 miles southwest of
Sacramento, a sign off the Road 31 exit reads "D.Q.U." What does this mean?;  
 -- R.W., Palo Alto  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ON THE ROAD TO HIGHER EDUCATION  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Action Line  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  A  It directs people to <ORGANIZATION>Deganawidah Quetzalcoatl University</ORGANIZATION>, now known as <ORGANIZATION>D-Q
University</ORGANIZATION>. It's a small, accredited two-year college with <PERCENT>65 percent</PERCENT> of its
300 students American Indians. The college opened in <DATE>1971</DATE> using the original
name. <PERSON>David Childress</PERSON>, a D-Q spokesman, says <PERSON>Deganawidah</PERSON> is a hero in Indian
culture. He says the <LOCATION>Mohawk</LOCATION> tribe uses the name in its religious ceremonies
and asked the college not to use it in its name. The school complied in <DATE>1977</DATE>.
<PERSON>Childress</PERSON> says <ORGANIZATION>Quetzalcoatl</ORGANIZATION> is a South American Indian mythical god of
learning and wisdom. D-Q <ORGANIZATION>University</ORGANIZATION> is between <ORGANIZATION>Winters</ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON>Davis</PERSON> in <LOCATION>Yolo
County.</LOCATION>;    Redeeming value;  Q  Boy, am I miffed. I went to <ORGANIZATION>Blockbuster Video</ORGANIZATION>
where there was a promotion that said, "Rent three videos and get a free
Subway sandwich." I rented three videos and received a coupon that stated,
"Good for a free 6-inch sandwich excluding double meat and double cheese
sandwiches." The coupon had a picture of a huge sandwich printed on it. I took
it into a Subway location to get my free sandwich and was told the coupon is
only redeemable for sandwiches up to <MONEY>$2.49</MONEY>. A <MONEY>$2.49</MONEY> sandwich is about equal to
mustard on a bun. The manager refused to fill my order for a six-inch sandwich
(excluding double meat and double cheese). This sure sounds like the old bait
and switch to me. Though it's only a stupid sandwich, I feel consumers should
band together. A coupon should be redeemable for what it says.;    -- <PERSON>Roger
Vance</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Santa Clara</LOCATION>; A  Agreed, says <PERSON>Scott Abbott</PERSON>, official with <ORGANIZATION>Subway
Development Co</ORGANIZATION>. Abbott apologizes for the rejection. He says you should have
received a free six-inch sandwich at any participating Subway location,
regardless of whether the sandwich is valued at more than <MONEY>$2.49</MONEY>. You didn't
specify which location you went to, so he's not sure if you went to a
participating spot. Abbott is making sure all franchise owners are aware that
people with those Blockbuster coupons are supposed to receive a free sandwich.
He says the <MONEY>$2.49</MONEY> value was supposed to be a guide and Blockbuster had
requested a value be printed on the coupons. Abbott is sending you a coupon
for a free sandwich compliments of <ORGANIZATION>Subway Development Co.</ORGANIZATION>;    Call for help; 
Q  I purchased a Pac Tel phone, model FE 5150. It was missing the wall/desk
mounting bracket. I have been trying to call the toll-free 800 number printed
on the instruction sheet. I get either a recording a busy signal but have
never been able to talk to a customer-service rep. I really need the bracket.;
   -- <PERSON>C. Alvarez</PERSON>, <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION>; A  The bracket is being shipped to you now, says
<PERSON>Amy Damianakes</PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION>Pac Tel Corp</ORGANIZATION>. Damianakes says <ORGANIZATION>Pac Tel</ORGANIZATION> sold the telephone
line a few years back to a company that wasn't ready to handle the volume of
sales. She says the reason you had trouble getting through to the toll-free
number was that the company didn't have a customer-service department until
recently. <PERSON>Damianakes</PERSON> did secure the mounting bracket and is making sure you
get it.  </TEXT>
