<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Columbia University</ORGANIZATION> is opening the first public gallery in <LOCATION>New
York</LOCATION> devoted exclusively to architecture.
   The gallery space in <PERSON>Buell Hall</PERSON>, which was constructed in <DATE>1876</DATE>,
consists of 4,100 square feet. The building also houses the <ORGANIZATION>School
of Architecture</ORGANIZATION>.
   The first exhibition in the new gallery opens <DATE>April 4</DATE> and runs
through <DATE>May 11</DATE>. ``The Filter of Reason: Work of <PERSON>Paul Nelson</PERSON>,''
focuses on the work of the American architect, movie set designer,
painter and critic who taught and practiced architecture in the
<LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>France</LOCATION> for more than 50 years.
   Nelson helped develop functionalism in the <DATE>1930s</DATE> and <DATE>'40s</DATE>, a
movement that rejected beaux-arts traditionalism.
   Elsewhere, the <ORGANIZATION>Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum</ORGANIZATION> has received an
unrestricted gift of <MONEY>$5 million</MONEY> from <ORGANIZATION>Akira Tobishima</ORGANIZATION>, president and
chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION>Tobishima Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, an international
engineering and construction company based in <LOCATION>Tokyo</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
